07071nam a22011055i 9789048529186DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182018ne     fo  d z      eng d  a2018483623  a97890485291867 a10.1515/97890485291862doi  a(DE-B1597)513243  a(OCoLC)1054092936  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL00aBH39b.I43 2018 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a111/.85090400aImages, Improvisations, Sound, and Silence from 1000 to 1800 - Degree Zero :bDegree Zero /ced. by Babette Hellemans, Alissa Jones Nelson. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b4 color plates, 16 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKnowledge Communities ;v600tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tOuverture -- tImages -- t1. The Two Bodies of the Virgin -- t2. The Three Ages of Man and the Materialization of an Allegory -- t3. Lapsus figurae -- tImprovisations -- t4. Drawing a Line and Questioning Art -- t5. Fall and Rise Again -- t6. Improvisation as a Chief Pillar of the Poetic Art in Persian Literary Tradition -- tSound -- t7. Intending the Listener -- t8. The Sovereign Ear -- t9. Where Sound and Meaning Part -- tSilence -- t10. Writing about Silence and the Secret in the Twelfth Century -- t11. An Arrangement of Silence -- t12. Dimidia Hora -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe act of drawing a line or uttering a word is often seen as integral to the process of making art. This is especially obvious in music and the visual arts, but applies to literature, performance, and other arts as well. These collected essays, written by scholars from diverse fields, take a historical view of the richness of creation out of nothing (creatio ex nihilo) in order to draw out debates, sometimes implicit and sometimes formally stated, about the production and reproduction of cultural meaning in a period of great change and novelty, between the beginnings of the medieval intellectual tradition and the imprint of the Enlightenment. The authors pose the following questions: Do tradition and creativity conflict with one another, or are they complementary? What are the tensions between composition and live performance? What is the role of the audience in perceiving the object of art? Are such objects fixed or flexible? What about the status of the event? Is the event part of creation, in the sense that it disturbs the still waters of historical continuity? These and other questions build on the foundation of Roland Barthes' concept of Degree Zero, offering new insights into what it means to create.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArtsxPhilosophy. 0aArts, Medieval. 0aArts, Modern. 0aSilence in literature. 0aSound in art. 0aSound in literature. 4aDiachronic. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aImage.  aLiterature.  aMusic.  aPremodern History.1 aDittmar, Pierre-Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsch, Andrea von Hülsen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiraud, Cédric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGohrab, Asghar Seyed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroot, Rokus de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHellemans, Babette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHellemans, Babette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJones Nelson, Alissa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKleiman, Irit Ruth, econtr